Introduction

In today's world, Spotify has become a platform used by many in order to not only stream the music we want, but to also recommend us music playlists curated based on our tastes. We are all especially intrigued by the data analytics implications of Spotify's year end music recap, as it allows us to reminisce on our music progression. This is one of the very minor applications of data analysis we see in our everyday lives, yet we look forward to it. We thought it would be interesting to analyze the data of Spotify tracks on a broader level and determine what factors correlate with a song being more popular, such as duration, explicitness, danceability and energy. Furthermore, we think that the applications of analyzing this dataset would be interesting because it gives us a glimpse into what Spotify recommendation algorithm does and what some changes or iterations of their algorithm may have looked like on a simple level. Spotify's recommendation algorithm essentially suggests songs to users based on the characteristics of songs that the user already is interested in and finds a pattern to curate playlists of similar song genres. The implications of this technique are vast, as it not only allows users to find new songs, but also to connect similar songs when creating different playlists for different moods.

We wanted to answer many questions by analyzing this dataset. What specific features/characteristics make a song more likely to be popular? How do attributes like energy or danceability influence the success of a song? How might the Spotify algorithm use these factors to recommend songs to users? Not only are these questions important for Spotify users to understand the answers to, but they are also integral for anyone interested in data science to learn about as this is a practical real-world application of how data science is used to further a platform's engagement.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Here, we want to gain a better understanding of the data based on the trends we discover.

We develop our conclusions and hypotheses for our dataset and test them initially. Typically, a range is created in order to assess data in a ranking format. Once the dataframe is split accordingly to the range, a test is conducted and the results are analyzed through a graph and conclusion that is displayed.

This section, as a whole, allows us to determine the patterns and relationships between certain variables, and gain a visual representation of this relationship.

Conclusion 1

First, we will explore the relationship between the danceability of the track and its popularity.
We will assume $\alpha = 0.05$.

Hypothesis 1

  • HO: The danceability of the track has no effect on the popularity of the track
  • HA: The danaceability of the track has an effect on the popularity of the track

Hypothesis Testing

We will first split the dataframe based on the songs' captured danceability rating.

print(f"The minimum value in danceability is {minDance} and the maximum value in danceability is {maxDance}")

The minimum value in danceability is 0.0 and the maximum value in danceability is 0.985

Based on this range, we will add a column called danceability_rank that ranks the danceability.

  • Low Danceability: 0.00 - 0.35
  • Medium Danceability: 0.36 - 0.70
  • High Danceability: 0.71 - 0.99
In[]:
def danceability_ranker(danceability):
    if 0.00 <= danceability <= 0.35:
        return 'Low'
    elif 0.36 <= danceability <= 0.70:
        return 'Medium'
    elif 0.71 <= danceability <= 0.99:
        return 'High'

df['danceability_rank'] = df['danceability'].apply(danceability_ranker)

Now, we will conduct the test.

In[]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

val = []
for (category, data) in groups:
  val.append(data['popularity'].values)

a, pval = f_oneway(*val)

pval
Out[]:
6.2782022111233374e-164

Conclusion

Because the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. We can conclude that our observed results are unlikely to occur under the hypothesis is that the danceability of the track has no effect on the popularity of the track. Post-hoc tests will need to be conducted because we rejected the null hypothesis, in order to identify which of the three levels of danceability is significantly different.

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.regplot(data=data, x=feature, y='popularity', scatter_kws={'alpha': 0.4}, line_kws={'color': 'red'})
    plt.title(f'{feature.capitalize()} vs Popularity', fontsize=16)
    plt.xlabel(feature.capitalize(), fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel('Popularity', fontsize=14)
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    plt.show()

These scatter plots with regression lines provide insights into the relationships between features and popularity:

Danceability vs. Popularity: A positive trend indicates that tracks with higher danceability tend to be more popular.

Energy vs. Popularity: A similar positive trend shows that energetic tracks are also likely to be more popular.

Valence vs. Popularity: Tracks with higher valence (happier tones) show a slight positive correlation with popularity.

The correlation heatmap highlights relationships between various features in the dataset. Key observations:

Instrumentalness is negatively correlated with popularity, suggesting that instrumental tracks are generally less popular.

Insights and Conclusion

Overall Analysis and Insights

This analysis provides a comprehensive look into the dataset, focusing on the factors influencing track popularity, audience preferences, and content trends. The findings reveal significant trends in how certain audio features, genres, and track characteristics contribute to a track's success. This helps provide insight into strategies for creating popular tracks. This can be used by producers and different streaming platforms (not only Spotify)to create better strategies to make tracks more successful and connect with listeners.

Popularity Trends

The majority of tracks in the dataset have low popularity, with only a few achieving high scores. This skewed distribution reflects a power-law dynamic in music consumption, where a minority of tracks dominate listener attention.This insight underscores the importance of identifying the attributes of highly popular tracks to replicate their success. For new and emerging artists, this dynamic creates a challenge for them to gain visibility and break into this competitive market. A way this dynamic can be changed is by having streaming platforms recommend lesser known tracks/artists in similar listening genres to help diversify listener attention. Streaming platforms can understand this imbalance to make changes and upgrades to their recommendation algorithms.

Feature Influence

Key features like danceability, energy, and valence exhibit strong positive correlations with popularity. Tracks that are upbeat, energetic, and emotionally uplifting tend to resonate better with audiences. Conversely, features like instrumentalness show a negative correlation, indicating that instrumental tracks are generally less popular. These relationships highlight the importance of crafting tracks with specific audio characteristics to appeal to broader audiences. For artists and producers, this means focusing on creating tracks that balance energy and emotional appeal. These insights can be used by streaming platforms in curating playlists and making recommendations to match each listener preferences. This will help keep users want to stick to their current platform due to the benefits it offers.

Genre Analysis

Genre plays a pivotal role in popularity. The analysis shows that a few dominant genres consistently outperform others in average popularity, pointing to their mass appeal. This finding suggests that focusing on these genres could yield higher engagement and revenue. However, it also presents an opportunity to explore underrepresented genres for niche markets. Streaming platforms can leverage this knowledge by recommending niche genres to users with specific tastes and interests in similar genres. By introducing users to new (potentially interesting) genres, platforms can help users broaden their interests. This will not only help make the user experience better but it will help build loyalty by showing the users the benefits the platform brings.

Explicit Content

Non-explicit tracks demonstrate slightly higher popularity on average compared to explicit tracks. This suggests that tracks with broader accessibilitycatering to all age groups and cultural contextstend to gain more traction. Non-explicit tracks is more likely to be included in family-friendly playlist and public spaces which can help boosting its reach and popularity. However, explicit content still holds value in specific genres or for targeting niche audiences. Artists and streaming platforms can capitalize on this info by creating both family-friendly playlists and genre-specific explicit playlists to cater to diverse listener preferences.

Correlation Patterns

The correlation heatmap revealed strong interconnections between features. For example, energy and loudness are highly correlated, emphasizing that energetic tracks often have higher loudness levels. Such insights provide actionable guidance for both music production and recommendation algorithms, ensuring tracks are fine-tuned to match listener preferences. Platforms can use this insights to improve recommendation algorithm. By understanding these correlations the platforms can help refine suggestions by grouping tracks with similar feature profiles. For example, recommending tracks with high energy and loudness to users who enjoy energetic playlists can improve user experience.

Strategic Implications

  • Production and Curation: Producers can prioritize traits like danceability and energy while focusing on top-performing genres to enhance the chances of success.
  • Marketing and Distribution: Non-explicit content and tracks with broadly appealing features can be promoted to wider audiences, while explicit tracks can target more niche, loyal listener bases.
  • Streaming and Recommendations: Platforms can leverage these insights to refine recommendation algorithms, ensuring that tracks with desirable attributes are surfaced to the right listeners.

Conclusion

This analysis offers actionable insights into the dynamics of music popularity. By identifying the attributes that contribute to a track's success and understanding the audience's preferences, stakeholders across production, marketing, and streaming can make data-driven decisions to maximize impact and revenue. By looking at key findings such as the importance of danceability, energy, as well as the role of genres and explicit content, helps provide a roadmap for crafting music that aligns with listener expectations while also finding places for innovation in underrepresented areas. This helps music artsists and producers to find and create music that can appeal to the most people. Future research could delve deeper into temporal trends and evolving genre preferences to predict shifts in listener behavior. Analyzing regional differences and their impact on genre preferences can help stakeholders adapt to global and local markets.
